fs, Brains and Breaking Chains -- tSocial Media as a Tool against Populist Appropriation of FoRB and for Promoting FoRB? -- tConclusion: The Case of Religious Freedom and Populism -- tList of Contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the cover design0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aPopulism is a growing threat to human rights. They are appropriated, distorted, turned into empty words or even their opposite. The contributors to this volume examine these practices using the example of freedom of religion or belief, a human right that has become a particular target of right-wing populists and extremists worldwide. The contributions not only show the rhetorical patterns of appropriation and distortion, but also demonstrate for various countries which social dynamics favor the appropriation in each case and propose how to strengthen human rights and the culture of debate in democratic societies.  afunded by transcript: Open Library 2024 (Politik)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aAppropriation. 4aFar-Right. 4aHuman Rights. 4aPopulism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aFundamentalism.  aPolitical Ideologies.  aPolitical Science.  aReligion.  aRight-wing Extremism.  aSociology of Religion.1 aBauer, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielefeldt, Heiner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuck, Katja Dorothea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarti, Juliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaou, Anna Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c